      h1 Gutenweb
      p Gutenweb is a typographical stylesheet. It is a CSS file ready to use for quick document generation in html (and epub).
      p Gutenweb aims to forgot styling when marking-up a document, as you do when you generate a document in LaTeX. It is suitable for not too complex documents
      p It adds some default styles which prioritize readability and they adapt to screen or print media. A lot of the concepts are taken from <a href="http://webtypography.net/">The Elements of Typographic Style Applied to the Web</a>.
      p This web page is using Gutenweb (plus, if your rendering engine supports it, background strips to show the vertical rhythm used), so you are right know seeing the look&amp;feel generated. Print to a PDF to look at the print version.
      h2 Setup
      p Get a copy in the <a href="https://github.com/laMarciana/gutenweb">official repository</a> or <a href="https://github.com/laMarciana/gutenweb/archive/master.zip">download the zip</a>.
      p Just copy <code>reset.css</code> and <code>gutenweb.css</code> to your css folder and add a link to the last one:
      pre.code
        code #{'<link rel="stylesheet" href="gutenweb.css">'}
      h2 Special formats
      h3 <code>.toc</code> for table of contents
      p To create a table of contents, mark-up a table with <code>.toc</code> as its <code>class</code>. Put the section titles inside <code>#{'<th>'}</code> and its page numbers inside <code>#{'<td>'}</code>:
      p Example:
      pre.code
        code  #{'<table class="toc">'}
              #{'  <tr>'}
              #{'    <th>Section 1</th><td>3</td>'}
              #{'  </tr>'}
              #{'  <tr>'}
              #{'    <th>Section 2</th><td>6</td>'}
              #{'  </tr>'}
              #{'</table>'}
      p Looks:
      table.toc
        tr
          <th>Section 1</th><td>3</td>
        tr
          <th>Section 2</th><td>6</td>
      h3 <code>.note</code> for notes
      p Example:
      pre.code
        code #{'<p class="note">I am small note</p>'}
      p Looks:
      p.note I am small note
      h3 <code>.caps</code> and <code>.nums</code> for uppercase and numeric strings
      p Uppercase and numeric string usually deserve a small increase in its letter-spacing.
      p Example:
      pre.code
        code #{'<p><span class="caps">UPPERCASE STRING</span></p>'}
             #{'<p><span class="num">936543476</span></p>'}
      p Looks:
      p: span.caps UPPERCASE STRING
      p: span.nums 936543476
      h3 <code>pre</code> with <code>.code</code> for block level code
      p For inline code, use simple <code>#{'<code>'}</code> tag. For block-level code, wrap it in a <code>#{'<pre>'}</code> tag with a <code>.code</code> class.
      p Example:
      pre.code
        code  #{'<pre class="code">'}
              #{'  <code>'}
              #{'    &lt;p&gt;Hello World!&lt;/p&gt;'}
              #{'  </code>'}
              #{'</pre>'}
      p Looks:
      pre.code
        code #{'<p>Hello World!</p>'}
      h3 <code>.verse</code> for verses
      p Example:
      pre.code
        code #{'<pre class="verse">Is not Gutenweb'}
             #{'such a nice'}
             #{'stylesheet?</pre>'}
      p Looks:
      pre.verse Is not gutenweb
                such a nice
                stylesheet?
